rComments: Professor Teramura was a really engaging prof. His lectures were super interesting, and he kept a fast pace which kept me interested. The course was reading heavy but if you go to lecture and note down the passages he talks about, the exam isn't too much of an issue. Lectures are actually really interesting, so I'd highly recommend going!
teacherRatingTags: ['Lecture heavy', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Get ready to read']

rComments: Very nice professor who seems passionate about what he teaches. Compared to my other English lit classes though, this one is definitely on the harder side. There's a LOT of material, and I didn't like how the final exam was structured comparing it to UtM's for the same course. You have to go to lecture or you won't fully understand the material.
teacherRatingTags: ['Lots of homework', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Get ready to read']

rComments: He knows a lot about his topic and relates a lot of history with the reading. He's very easy to get in touch with but gives A LOT of readings. Most of them are poems but some are very long plays/"Books". Also suggested to the class during a lecture to LITERALLY cut one of our textbooks in half so it wouldn't be heavy for us.
Reads a script and doesn't pause to breathe.
teacherRatingTags: ['Lecture heavy', 'Get ready to read', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: Really eccentric guy. It's pretty cool that he facilitates learning across disciplines, focusing on history, linguistics, politics, etc. He taught about the structure and mechanics of poetry more than anything else. Cool perspective.

Misha is an amazing prof! You can tell he cares very much about his content and his students. He puts a lot of works on the syllabus but its definitely just because he's so excited about the course. As long as you generally know what's going on in them you'll be fine. I would definitely take another one of his classes.
